\subsection{Data Transformations and Cleaning}

\subsubsection{Training and Testing Split}

We randomly split the 517 available observations into a training and testing set, using a ratio of approximately 75/25. The testing set was held out from the model selection process so as not to introduce bias.

\subsubsection{Area}

Since there were many observations with zero area values, we modeled the response in most cases as the transformation

$$\log(\textbf{area}+1)$$

This transformation has the property that all zero values remain unchanged while the positive observations are presented in a logarithmic scale.

\subsubsection{rain}
There are only 7 nonzero \textbf{rain} values: Considered \textbf{rainbin}

\subsubsection{FFMC}

As observed in Figure \ref{fig:hFFMC}, the original version of the predictor FFMC is negatively skewed. Since log transformations are generally useful for positive skewness, we can try to normalize this predictor by reflecting it, adding an appropriate value to make it positive, and finally applying a log transformation. 
$$f(\textbf{FFMC}) = \log (-\textbf{FFMC}+\max(\textbf{FFMC})+1)$$
 
 

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics{hist_FFMC.jpeg}
    \caption{Histogram of FFMC Variable}
    \label{fig:hFFMC}
\end{figure}

Figure \ref{fig:TrFFMC} shows the final distribution of this transformed variable.

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics{TrFFMC.jpeg}
    \caption{Histogram of FFMC Variable}
    \label{fig:TrFFMC}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Observation Order}

We also noticed a trend in observation order with respect to \textbf{Larea}: this is likely due to the fact that this data came from two different data sets which were combined manually. \cite{1} When combining the two data sets, it seems that the first set was sorted by \textbf{area}, while the second set was ordered chronologically. This prevented us from using a time series approach on the data set in its entirety.
 
\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width = .7\textwidth]{obsnord.png}
    \label{fig:obsnord}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Selection Criteria}

The Mallow's CP criterion does not apply in the MLR scenario because we cannot assume that the full model exactly describes behavior of burn area. Also, since the available predictors do not explain much of the variability in the response, adjusted $R^2$ is being influenced more by the number of variables in the model than the amount of variability explained, in some cases turning negative. This is why we chose to compare models based on the BIC criterion.

